{
 "level": "B2",
 "intro": "In this topic, you compare <strong>Future Continuous</strong> and <strong>Future Perfect Continuous</strong>: are we asking <strong>what will be happening then</strong> or <strong>how long the action will already have been happening by then</strong>?",
 "rules": [
  {
   "label": "FUTURE CONTINUOUS",
   "color": "amber",
   "text": "<strong>will be + V-ing</strong> for an action that will be <strong>in progress</strong> at a specific future moment.",
   "example": "At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll be studying. / This time tomorrow, they'll be driving home."
  },
  {
   "label": "FUTURE PERFECT CONTINUOUS",
   "color": "rose",
   "text": "<strong>will have been + V-ing</strong> for <strong>duration or process</strong> up to a future limit or moment.",
   "example": "By 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll have been studying for three hours. / By next month, she'll have been living here for a year."
  },
  {
   "label": "KEY QUESTION",
   "color": "blue",
   "text": "Ask yourself: <strong>what will be happening then?</strong> or <strong>how long will it have been happening by then?</strong>",
   "example": "future process at that moment / duration up to that moment"
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "1. Quick comparison",
 "intro": "Both forms talk about a process, but they look at it differently:",
 "rows": [
  {
   "en": "Future Continuous",
   "ua": "what will be happening at a future moment",
   "note": "At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll be working."
  },
  {
   "en": "Future Perfect Continuous",
   "ua": "how long the process will already have been going on by a future moment",
   "note": "By 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll have been working for three hours."
  },
  {
   "en": "this time tomorrow / at 8 p.m. tomorrow",
   "ua": "we ask what will be happening then",
   "note": "This time tomorrow, she'll be flying to Warsaw."
  },
  {
   "en": "by then / by the time / by next month",
   "ua": "we ask how long the action will already have been happening by that point",
   "note": "By the time you arrive, we'll have been waiting for an hour."
  },
  {
   "en": "future point vs duration up to a future point",
   "ua": "ongoing action then vs ongoing duration before then",
   "note": "will be working vs will have been working"
  }
 ],
 "warning": "If the focus is an <strong>action in progress at a future point</strong>, choose <strong>Future Continuous</strong>. If the focus is the <strong>duration of the process up to that point</strong>, choose <strong>Future Perfect Continuous</strong>."
}

{
 "title": "2. Forms grid",
 "intro": "Compare the basic affirmative, negative, and question patterns for both forms.",
 "items": [
  {
   "label": "Future Continuous",
   "title": "Affirmative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + will be + V-ing: I will be working."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Continuous",
   "title": "Negative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + won't be + V-ing: I won't be working."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Continuous",
   "title": "Question",
   "subtitle": "Will + subject + be + V-ing? Will you be studying at 8 p.m.?"
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Perfect Continuous",
   "title": "Affirmative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + will have been + V-ing: I will have been working."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Perfect Continuous",
   "title": "Negative",
   "subtitle": "Subject + won't have been + V-ing: I won't have been working."
  },
  {
   "label": "Future Perfect Continuous",
   "title": "Question",
   "subtitle": "Will + subject + have been + V-ing? How long will you have been studying by 8 p.m.?"
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "3. When the meaning changes",
 "sections": [
  {
   "label": "A future point",
   "color": "amber",
   "description": "Choose <strong>Future Continuous</strong> when you want to show an action <strong>in progress</strong> at a specific future moment.",
   "examples": [
    {
     "en": "At 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll be studying in the library.",
     "ua": "The focus is on what will be happening exactly then."
    },
    {
     "en": "This time tomorrow, she'll be flying to Warsaw.",
     "ua": "We ask what will be in progress at that future moment."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "label": "Duration up to the limit",
   "color": "rose",
   "description": "Choose <strong>Future Perfect Continuous</strong> when it matters <strong>how long</strong> the action will have been continuing by a future point, or when the process stretches up to that limit.",
   "examples": [
    {
     "en": "By 8 p.m. tomorrow, I'll have been studying for three hours.",
     "ua": "The focus is on the duration before 8 p.m."
    },
    {
     "en": "By next month, she'll have been working here for a year.",
     "ua": "The focus is on a process that will already have lasted some time by a future point."
    },
    {
     "en": "By the time you arrive, we'll have been waiting for an hour.",
     "ua": "The question is not what will be happening then, but the duration before that moment."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "label": "A paired contrast",
   "color": "blue",
   "description": "The context is similar, but the focus changes: <strong>what will be happening then</strong> or <strong>how long it will already have been happening by then</strong>.",
   "examples": [
    {
     "en": "At 8 p.m., they'll be waiting for the train.",
     "ua": "We ask what will be happening at that moment."
    },
    {
     "en": "By 8 p.m., they'll have been waiting for the train for an hour.",
     "ua": "We ask how long the process will already have lasted by that time."
    }
   ],
   "note": "<strong>at this time / at 8 p.m. tomorrow</strong> often points to <strong>Future Continuous</strong>, while <strong>by then / by the time / by next month / for an hour</strong> often points to <strong>Future Perfect Continuous</strong>."
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "4. Typical mistakes",
 "items": [
  {
   "label": "Mistake 1",
   "color": "amber",
   "title": "Using Future Perfect Continuous when you only want to say what will be happening then",
   "wrong": "❌ This time tomorrow, I'll have been taking the exam.",
   "right": "✅ This time tomorrow, I'll be taking the exam."
  },
  {
   "label": "Mistake 2",
   "color": "rose",
   "title": "Using Future Continuous when the duration up to the limit matters",
   "wrong": "❌ By 8 p.m., I'll be studying for three hours.",
   "right": "✅ By 8 p.m., I'll have been studying for three hours."
  },
  {
   "label": "Mistake 3",
   "color": "blue",
   "title": "Forgetting been in Future Perfect Continuous",
   "wrong": "❌ By next month, she will have working here for a year.",
   "right": "✅ By next month, she will have been working here for a year."
  },
  {
   "label": "Mistake 4",
   "color": "violet",
   "title": "Mixing up at that time and by that time",
   "wrong": "❌ By the time you arrive, we'll be waiting for an hour.",
   "right": "✅ By the time you arrive, we'll have been waiting for an hour."
  }
 ]
}

{
 "title": "5. A short decision guide",
 "items": [
  "Do you need to show that the action <strong>will be in progress at a future moment</strong>? → choose <strong>Future Continuous</strong>.",
  "Do you need to show <strong>how long</strong> the action will already have been continuing <strong>by a future moment</strong>? → choose <strong>Future Perfect Continuous</strong>.",
  "Markers like <strong>this time tomorrow</strong> or <strong>at 8 p.m. tomorrow</strong> often point to <strong>will be + V-ing</strong>.",
  "Markers like <strong>by then</strong>, <strong>by the time</strong>, <strong>by next month</strong> plus the idea of <strong>for / how long</strong> often point to <strong>will have been + V-ing</strong>.",
  "If you are unsure, say the question out loud: <strong>what will be happening then?</strong> or <strong>how long will it have been happening by then?</strong>"
 ]
}

